RACE.RACE_TEXT: WOODBINE RACE 1 5F All Weather Track CR: 75. Maiden Claiming Purse 36300. FOR MAIDENS, TWO YEARS OLD. Weight, 121 lbs. Claiming Price $15,000.
RACE.FOOTNOTES: IM A SOUPERMAN pressed between rivals down the backside, cruised to the lead on the outside at the quarter pole, opened up convincingly in mid-stretch and comfortably came home for the victory. MATICULANT stalked outside in the two path down the back straight, shifted inwards to the rail commencing a run with three eighths remaining, was full of run three wide at the quarter pole and easily bested the rest at the finish for the solid runner up finish. SQUEEZETHESHARMAN had a good position down the backside all alone watching the engaging trio early on, was roused three furlongs from the wire, closed in late with a good stretch kick and finished up to be a non threatening third at the line. BLUE TANGO prompted three wide on the outside down the back straight, could not match strides with the top two up front three furlongs from home and willingly finished up in the lane to capture a minor share in the end. GLORIOUS REVENGE assumed command down the backstretch, offered no resistance to the winner making a move at the quarter pole and faltered on the rail at the furlong marker. DRILLHALL was away slowly on the break to trail by many, showed some energy picking up rivals on the rail running around the bend, could not overcome that poor start and made little impression through the stretch. DELIRIO stalked on the rail in the beginning, could not quicken with others through the turn and was not a presence in the run down the lane. PERSEVERE was void of speed down the backside having one beat which was the slow starter, offered little response when scrubbed on in midturn and could not get involved in the stretch drive. SPIRIT OF SEATTLE settled in midfield on the outside in the early going, was bearing out through the turn, basically was eased with five sixteenths to run and galloped down the stretch crossing the finish.

RACE.RACE_TEXT: WOODBINE RACE 2 1 1/16M All Weather Track CR: 68. Claiming Purse 34400. FOR FILLIES AND MARES THREE YEARS OLD AND UPWARD WHICH HAVE NEVER WON TWO RACES. Three Year Olds, 123 lbs.; Older, 125 lbs. Non-winners Of A Race At A Mile Or Over In 2023 Allowed 2 lbs. Claiming Price $10,000, if for $9,500, allowed 2 lbs. (Races Where Entered For $7,500 Or Less Not Considered For Allowances).
RACE.FOOTNOTES: REINS OF PURPLE was unhurried trailing in the early stages, improved smartly four deep finding a good rhythm down the backside, loomed four wide around runners on the final turn and wore down the leaders through the lane to get up right at the wire in a well timed stretch run. MOON POOL tracked the frontrunner on the rail on the first turn, took closer order to press the pacesetter outside at the half, dueled with rivals on each side with five sixteenths to run, determinedly surged to the lead with a sixteenth left and just missed in a gutsy effort losing the nod at the wire. SERENADING HALL was content to track three wide on the outside on the first turn, prompted the pace three wide outside rivals at the half, poked her head in front between rivals at the quarter pole, battled stubbornly down the stretch but was outgamed in the final sixteenth. KEY STROKE stalked three wide on the outside having one beat on the first turn, stalked in the third flight in the three path between horses down the backstretch, was hard ridden three wide midpoint around the final bend, had a chance for a piece of the prize four wide straightening out for the drive and showed some late interest to settle on the fringes in the end. TOTAL BETTY travelled between foes in mid-pack, was tucked in on the rail behind the front trio with a half left to run, angled outside when urged for more with five sixteenths left to go, was in range in the three path in upper stretch and evened out down the lane. TURF AND SURF was unchallenged taking this field into the first turn, maintained the lead with a narrow advantage four furlongs from the wire, was headed outside midway on the far turn, gave way when steadied mildly inside the quarter pole and yielded in mid stretch. MIZZ GEMMA stalked close the back with runners on each side, closed the gap down the back straight to be in the thick of things in midfield at the half, was asked for more run three eighths from home and had little run to offer in the stretch drive. MENAGERIE stalked near the rear on the rail, was shuffled back to trail on the fence in a tightly packed bunch at the half, made no headway running on the final turn and could not get into contention driving to the finish line.

RACE.FOOTNOTES: AMBER LIGHT took control from the onset, was uncontested while opening up in hand throughout the turn and was much the best dominating down the stretch easily extending the advantage crossing the finish line. SERENADE AT SEA tracked the frontrunner down the backside, was urged to go after the winner on the turn, but could not close the gap and chased the winner in vain running to the wire and comfortably was the second best on this day. CANDY STREET was allowed to settle trailing inside in the early going, progressed well on the fence through the backstretch, rallied on the rail passing foes on the turn and finished up mildly down the lane to hold for third in a strung out field at the finish. GLENHOLME hopped slightly on the break, stalked five deep near the back of the pack outside rivals down the backside, circled four wide outside foes three eighths from the wire, swung out widest in the six path at the top of the lane, levelled out some in mid-stretch but held on for a small piece of the prize in the end. HIP TO YOUR TRICKS settled near the rear three wide between foes at the half, began to pick up the pace three wide in midturn, was in range for a share in the five path turning for home and lost the duel for the minor award in the stretch. MIGHTY PELE stalked inside in the third flight down the back straight, was scrubbed on three furlongs left to run, could not maintain position running around the bend and showed little effort driving to the finish line. WILD CONVERSATION travelled near the rear in the two path with foes on each side, could not match strides with others commencing a run three eighths from the wire and had little to show on the fence in the stretch run. THE SWAYZE EXPRESS stalked on the third flight three wide outside runners down the backside, offered a brief run from the three furlong marker through the the top of the stretch and gave way in the final furlong.

RACE.RACE_TEXT: WOODBINE RACE 6 1 1/16M All Weather Track CR: 83. Claiming Purse 34400. FOR THREE YEAR OLDS AND UPWARD WHICH HAVE NEVER WON TWO RACES. Three Year Olds, 123 lbs.; Older, 125 lbs. Non-winners Of A Race At A Mile Or Over In 2023 Allowed 2 lbs. Claiming Price $10,000, if for $9,500, allowed 2 lbs. (Races Where Entered For $7,500 Or Less Not Considered For Allowances).
RACE.FOOTNOTES: ANSELMO stalked in the third flight three wide outside runners down the back straight, was ridden to go on between horses midway on the far turn, swung out with momentum in the six path at the top of the stretch, drifted in slightly under right handed encouragement nearing the sixteenth pole and got up for the measured win. ROBITAILLE was on the rail part of the tracking trio down the backstretch, waited patiently on the fence around the final bend, was in the mix in the two path straightening out for the stretch drive, drifted out some under left handed urging in mid-stretch, ran on well in deep stretch but could not match strides with the winner late. GROOM LAKE trailed the field down the backstretch, began to pick up rivals running inside at the quarter pole, swung outside six wide for the drive to the wire and closed in gamely late to capture third money at the finish line. STRONGER TOGETHER prompted the issue outside early, was content to shadow the pacesetter down the backside, came under a hard ride between horses midway on the far turn, continued to battle on being in the hunt in three path at the top of the lane, was steadied in tight quarters nearing the sixteenth pole and recovered late to get up for a minor role at the end. AIR FORCE RESERVE was under a snug hold dictating terms comfortably up front down the backside, continued going easily up top rounding the final turn, was clinging to the lead on the fence with a furlong to go, weakened late and was swallowed up by runners outside in the final seventy yards. BARTICA travelled on the inside stalking in the third flight down the backstretch, tried to start a rally shifted just off the fence with five sixteenths to go, could not quicken with the eventual winner who was rallying with him outside at the quarter pole and showed some interest down the lane to offering a mild finish in deep stretch. BILL NEEDLE travelled in the second flight between foes watching the front two down the back straight, began to inch closer to the leaders when coaxed three wide at the three eighths marker, loomed in the four path with runners on either side turning for home, could not find another gear late and wilted at the furlong marker. C R HOT SHOT tracked three wide on the outside in the second flight down the backstretch, was nudged four wide three furlongs from the line, could not offer a run on the final turn and was empty for the stretch drive. RACE.RACE_TEXT: WOODBINE RACE 7 1 1/16M All Weather Track CR: 85. Claiming Purse 51000. FOR THREE YEAR OLDS AND UPWARD WHICH HAVE NEVER WON TWO RACES. Three Year Olds, 123 lbs.; Older, 125 lbs. RACE.FOOTNOTES: FLAWLESS RULER was content to be alone watching the front end speedster set the quick fractions down the backside, patiently began to reel in the pacesetter around the bend in the final turn, pounced to the lead in mid-stretch outside and drew off comfortably for the win. VICTORIA'S CHIEF was brushed outside at the start, settled in mid-pack two wide on the outside down the backstretch, waited behind a trio of runner on the far turn, angled four wide for the drive, burst between horses nearing the sixteenth pole and closed belatedly to be a non threatening second. LESLIE CHOW stalked near the rear having two beat down the backside, made an early move at the half picking up horses, rallied four wide circling foes on the far turn to be in the hunt in the for path turning for home, could not sustain the run and was outkicked for second money in deep stretch. COLONEL MUSTARD settled in third place in a strung out field down the backstretch, came under a vigorous ride between foes in midturn, continued to battle in the two path with runners on each side for a share of the prize turning for home and was one paced in deep stretch to settle on the fringes in the end. SILVER SMOKE was sent to the lead into the first turn, opened up to a commanding advantage under brisk fractions down the back straight, was asking for the wire shortening stride on the fence in upper stretch and emptied out at the sixteenth pole. ARAMOS brushed inside rival on the break, co-trailed inside with four furlongs to run, made little impact when roused three furlongs from the finish and passed tired runners in the stretch. MIDWAY MISCHIEF travelled in midfield on the rail down the backside, edged closer inside to be part of the tracking pack at the half, was urged on the fence keeping pace with others outside in the final turn, found little in the drive and retreated on the rail at the furlong pole. KILLARY co-trailed on the outside at the half, was asked but offered little response throughout the far turn making no gain and could not get interested in the drive down the stretch.

RACE.FOOTNOTES: HICKSY prompted the pace inside in the beginning, switched outside at the half mile marker, took over control midway around the bend, was getting out even under right handed encouragement at the quarter pole, shortened stride while on the wrong lead through the stretch but stubbornly prevailed at the wire. MONSTRODAMOUS had a good position watching the front pair down the backside, was hard ridden chasing the winner at the quarter pole, angled in to the two path not giving up at the top of the lane and stubbornly battled to the finish, just missing in the end with a solid effort. UPSTART GENTLEMAN was allowed to settle trailing down the backside, could see the field starting to lengthen stride through the turn, opted for the overland route when coming up to fading runners at the quarter pole, swung outside widest in the eight path driving to the wire, was laying in not switching leads at the furlong pole, finally straightened out late under left handed urging and closed strongly in deep stretch for third money. WENJACK was five deep on the outside near the back of the pack at the half, rallied four wide picking up horses with three eighths to go, swung outside in the eight path to be in the mix for share at the top of the stretch and gamely finished up just losing the battle for third nearing the wire. CARMENOOTZ stalked near the back on the inside, improved position at the half, crept closer on the turn in the third flight inside, shifted out in the five path with a chance for a share driving to the finish and ran on willingly to the wire. TRANQUILITY BASE was unhurried down the backstretch having one beat with a half remaining, put in a mild fence run through the turn when roused, had a chance for a minor share in the two path at the furlong marker but stalled inside in the final seventy yards. BOCELLI stalked near the rear on the outside down the back straight, offered a mild run between horses in the three path around the turn and showed some late interest in the final furlong but could not get involved at the wire. BIG INVESTMENT stumbled badly on the break, had one beat in the early going, was urged down the backside improving on the fence for better inside position, continued to rally on the rail through the turn, shifted outside to the four path to be in the mix for a share turning for home, could not find more late and faltered between rivals at the furlong marker. BEYOND BORDERS stalked between runners in mid-pack, was roused outside in the third flight around the bend making little progress, shifted out to the six path for the stretch run and yielded at the furlong marker. COMMANDER TOM assumed command on the outside in the beginning, was collared outside three furlongs out, offer no resistance to the winner and backed away through the field on the fence in mid-stretch.
